title Silo the IronBeetle build patterns into the Neth ladder, merged with work-in-progress
prompt Keaton asked to source relevant roadmap and granular-task inspiration from our matklad/IronBeetle summaries, silo the insights for our own goals, merge with work-in-progress, and continue aligning everything with the compass.
think Distinguished this pass from the existing matklad-essays distillation (20260712-093812), which already holds the general craft lessons. The IronBeetle STREAM is different in kind: a person building a single-threaded, deterministic, append-only, replicated state machine in the open — which is almost exactly what Neth is and what our whole fold-over-a-signed-log spine already is. So the particulars are buildable patterns for laps we have open, not admiration.
think Read the compass first to align (foundations -> grain -> Two Rooms -> active-designing -> TASKS -> ROADMAP), then read the episodes most relevant to live threads: ep004/ep040 (small serial core, everything else pipelined), ep014 (graduated trust — authoritative at source, verified on repair, never truncate committed), ep043 (written is not acknowledged — the manifest is the moment of truth; free-after-one-checkpoint), ep018 (deterministic seeded replay as the debugging substrate; two correct rules meeting in a wrong place). Siloed each in our own words, gratitude kept in gratitude/ironbeetle, no phrasing carried.
think Turned the six siloed patterns into concrete, provable Neth laps rather than leaving them as admiration: small serial core (the fold+append is the only ordered step, pipeline the rest); two-posture root install (trust the issuing monarch's current-view root at issue, re-verify any repair root's hash-chain, never truncate committed — building on the deterministic-root witness already green); apply-step crash safety (root application distinct from root writing, crash in the window costs nothing); and a genuinely new capability we lack — a seeded deterministic-simulation harness so a liveness/safety bug replays byte-for-byte, named as a horizon. Also mapped written-is-not-acknowledged onto Mantra bolt visibility and free-after-one-checkpoint onto Tally/Amber/Mantra.
think Merged into work-in-progress per the compass: the siloed study is the study->design bridge; TASKS gained a Neth build ladder subsection (each lap provable before the next, all gated after the green root witness), active-reviving's Neth row now points at the ladder, and TAME_GUIDANCE gained a release-after-one-checkpoint discipline note scoped to checkpoint/rewind subsystems only (ordinary season memory keeps its plain release). What changed is the granularity of the Neth ladder, not the direction — the patterns fit the grain (append-only fold, bounds, witnesses, safety-first) rather than importing anything foreign.
obs The strongest single find is the seeded deterministic-simulation harness: it is a real capability we do not yet have (our witnesses are happy/unwelcome assertions, not fault injection), it is the honest home for proving Neth safe under partial failure, and it extends "pin what the bench reports, never predict it" exactly. Named as a horizon so it does not jump ahead of the real replica laps.
file external-research/20260714-041542_ironbeetle-patterns-for-the-neth-ladder.md why: the six siloed built-system patterns, each tied to a live thread, with roadmap merges; clean-room kept
file work-in-progress/TASKS.md why: Neth build ladder subsection merged (small serial core · two-posture install · apply-step crash safety · simulation horizon · Mantra apply step)
file active-reviving/README.md why: Neth revival row points at the ladder and names the next laps
file context/TAME_GUIDANCE.md why: release-after-one-checkpoint discipline note, scoped to checkpoint/rewind subsystems
recommend keep-going — study siloed and merged, direction unchanged, granularity sharpened; all Neth laps gated after the green root witness and none jump ahead of real replicas.
